<article id="post-1122" class="hentry page publish post-1 odd author-admin">

	
	
		<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="page-title entry-title"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/about-us/">About Us</a></h1>		</header><!-- .entry-header -->

		<div class="entry-content">
			<p style="text-align: left;"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/pagebanner1.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1128" alt="pagebanner" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/pagebanner1.png" width="590" height="43"/></a></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;">The Blog</h2>
<blockquote><p>“I have always been a reader; I have read at every stage of my life, and there has never been a time when reading was not my greatest joy.”</p>
<p>— From <em>The Thirteenth Tale</em> by Diane Setterfield</p></blockquote>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><em><strong>A Novel Idea</strong></em> has been around since 2008, when I decided to start blogging my way through my first ever 50 Book Challenge. During this process, I discovered that talking about books was just as enjoyable as reading them. The blog became a means to recommend beloved books, as well as to vent about the ones that just didn&#8217;t work out. And despite a long hiatus over two very crazy years in my life, I&#8217;ve found myself coming back here time and time again. Books have been my friends and my escape since childhood. Before I could read them on my own, the highlight of my night was choosing which bedtime story would be read to me. The driving force behind my reviews is an unconditional love for reading. But as eclectic as my tastes might be, I am actually really selective about what I read; that&#8217;s why I also focus on answering the questions other discerning readers will be asking. I want you to know, by the end of my review, whether or not that book will be for you. And most of all, I want to make sure you don&#8217;t miss a book that was meant for you.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">A lot of big changes have taken place here at my little blog over the years, most recently (and most awesomely) the addition of my lovely co-blogger, Alix! I was lucky enough to meet her through our teeny tiny book club last year, and we became friends through a shared love of books. My younger sister Nina also contributes reviews here every once in a while. These ladies really make the place classier, don&#8217;t you think??</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Want more? You can also read our review policy <a title="Review Policy" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/review-policy/">here</a>!</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;">Disclosure</h2>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We&#8217;re lucky enough to receive some of our books as free advanced copies from the publisher, but we don&#8217;t receive any type of compensation for writing the reviews featured on this blog. Every review here is representative of our personal, honest opinions and observations regarding what we read. We will always cite exactly where/how we received the book in question at the end of the review.</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">The Reviewers</span></h2>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/greads_paola.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-1123" alt="greads_paola" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/greads_paola-234x300.jpg" width="140" height="180"/></a> <strong>PAOLA</strong> is a 25-year old teacher, blogger, and lifelong bibliophile. She lives in Las Vegas, NV with her husband and an extremely enthusiastic rat terrier. Among her favorite authors are Robin McKinley, Kate Morton, Garth Nix, Lisa See, Philip Pullman, and Neil Gaiman. Paola cultivates bad habits such as reading in bed, reading while eating, and reading while walking. An autographed copy of <em>The Last Unicorn</em> numbers among her most treasured possessions, along with the world&#8217;s most battered, coverless, dog-eared, yellowed copy of <em>Little House in the Big Woods</em> &#8212; she&#8217;s had it since the fourth grade, after all. Please be aware that Paola has declared war against love triangles and has vowed to eradicate them from the face of the Earth, with very few, very exceptional exceptions. Good books have been known to leave her a shameless, weeping mess for days afterward. You can find her on <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com/user/show/6778343-paola-a-novel-idea" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com']);" target="_blank">Goodreads</a>, follow her on <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://twitter.com/_anovelidea" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://twitter.com']);" target="_blank">Twitter</a>, or simply stalk this blog, because she practically lives here.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/2009660.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-1665 alignleft" alt="2009660" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/2009660.jpg" width="140" height="180"/></a>ALIX</strong> is in her late twenties, a project manager by day and bookworm-in-training by night. She has always been an avid reader, receiving awards from her high school for having taken out the most books. Alix loves reading in English and French. She will sometimes pick up a French book in its English translation if the cover is prettier (she also really likes pretty things) and has her bookshelves organized by book cover colour. A fan of all things British (the royalty, Downtown Abbey, tea, Colin Firth), Alix will forever hold Jane Austen in a special place in her heart as her novels were the first works of classic English fiction she read as an impressionable teenager. Alix is mostly reading YA (enough with the love triangles already!) and romance novels (a genre people are often too quick to dismiss) these days. She can be found reading into the wee hours of the morning, spotted with her nose buried in a book on her daily commute and browsing books on <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com/hiboudeminuit" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com']);">Goodreads</a>.</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Contributors</span></h2>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/greads_patricia.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-1124" alt="greads_patricia" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437im_/http://novelideareviews.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/greads_patricia.jpg" width="140" height="180"/></a><strong>NINA</strong> is a fairly artistic hermit of questionable age, reliability, and emotional stability. She values her hair more than her sanity and is thoroughly incapable of multitasking. She also likes music, and collects black shirts. Her place of residence is constantly TBA; sometimes she lives in South-East Asia, sometimes on the west coast of North America, but regardless of location is infamously difficult to contact. She likes words and people who know what to do with them, some of her favorite such people being Cormac McCarthy, Philip Pullman, T. S. Eliot, Bob Dylan, and Samuel Beam. You can probably find her desk cluttered with loose-leaf paper covered in doodles, obscure reminders, and quotes ranging from One Piece to Also Sprach Zarathustra. (These bits of paper are almost never dated. She should work on that.) Nina doesn’t like social networking – or, come to think of it, being social in general – but if it is a matter of Life or Death you can probably reach her through <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com/user/show/17923435-patricia" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-article','https://web.archive.org/web/20130618071437/http://www.goodreads.com']);" target="_blank">Goodreads</a> or her sister, Paola. She will attempt to be interesting, but makes no promises.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->

